<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911004-0016</DOCNO><DOCID>911004-0016.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Farmland Dairies Inc.:   New Jersey Firm Violated   Antitrust Law, Judge Finds</HL><DATE>10/04/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><IN>COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)</IN><NS>COMMODITIES MARKET (CMD)ANTITRUST NEWS (TST)</NS><RE>NEW JERSEY (NJ)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Farmland Dairies Inc., Wallington, N.J., one of thestate's largest dairy companies, was found by a New JerseySuperior Court judge to have violated antitrust law when it&quot;conspired to destroy&quot; a competitor that had severed businessties with Farmland.   In 1985, Ideal Dairy Farms Inc., ended a relationship withFarmland under which Ideal had been a distributor ofFarmland's milk products. In a lawsuit filed in New Jersey,Ideal alleged that Farmland retaliated by encouraging itsother distributors to selectively undercut prices to takeaway Ideal's customers.</LP><TEXT>   In a decision, Judge Paul B. Thompson found that Farmlandhad engaged in predatory pricing against Ideal and hadviolated antitrust law. He awarded Ideal $1.3 million incompensatory damages and $1.5 million in punitive damages.   Marc Goldman, Farmland's president, said the company wouldappeal. &quot;I felt there was no merit to the case when it wasinstituted, and despite this decision I still feel that way,&quot;Mr. Goldman said. &quot;There was really no element of antitrust .. . that would justify any finding.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>